Update N2:

Nord Stream 2 is currently appealing the Danish Energy Agency's demand for a new application for a third route. The Nord Stream 2 is seeking to have the demand declared illegal and will potentially sue for compensation from the Danish state, as the delay in the Danish approval procedure, very likely, will be substantial. The potential repercussions might push the Danish state to fast-forward the case through the Danish Energy Agency, though it seems just as likely that it will stick to it's current strategy of dragging the process.. Hence, I struggle to see if adjustments should be made to the current assigned probabilities. As of now, they will remain the same.

Update: The news is that Nord Stream 2 company are looking into lawsuit against the Danish State has reached Danish Media https://borsen.dk/nyheder/politik/artikel/1/382769/dansk_noel_om_nord_stream_2_kan_koste_russerne_milliarder_-_og_de_vil_have_erstatning_for_tabet.html#cxrecs_s - It could pressure for a decision, so I am holding on to my forecast, that the most likely scenario is that approval will land before 30 November.
I am rather confident that Denmark will not approve the construction of Nord Stream 2 through its territorial zone or EEZ before December 2019.

Update (9/06/19) The continuos pressures by Gazprom on Denmark to allow the construction of the pipelines on its EEZ (https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-forum-gazprom-nord-stream/gazprom-nord-stream-2-danish-part-to-be-built-in-five-weeks-maximum-ifax-idUSKCN1T826E and https://www.rt.com/business/461296-nord-stream-us-denmark-novak/) witness Russian reluctance in decising to adopt the plan B - the ones which would allow, at a higher cost, to avoid Denamrk's EEZ. This insistence made me change slightly my forecast. My idea remains that the process might take a while, if Denmark will ever give the consent. Nevertheless, while in the past I completely excluded Denmark's approval before the end of August, now I decided to put a precautios 1% possibility, and I increased slighlty the possibility for the approval to arrive by the end of November.

After the Danish elections, it is more than likely the opposition, led by the Social Democrats, will form the new governing coalition. This opposition as well as dissension within the past governing coalition led to the stalling of approval of Nord Stream 2. Now that the most vocal critiques of the pipeline are in power, approval will most assuredly not going to happen in the first few months of the new government and it's considerably less likely that'll it'll happen at all before December 1st.

Nordstream II continues to be surrounded by potential conflicts and complications. With the US sanctions and the potential trouble from the EU gas directive of May 23rd, the project is challenged. Moreover, Manfred Weber's fight against the pipeline continues and environmental interest groups have voiced their support for Weber's endeavour to halt the gas project. The project received zero attention in the Danish election campaign (which perhaps was expected), but it underlines that it is not a currently a major political case in Denmark. I suspect Denmark will continue it's route of 'avoidance' and push the decision as far as it can - hoping it will become an EU decision. I adjust my probabilities slightly, and make it 50% likelihood of the decision being made between September 1st and November 30th (closer to november) and not before December 1st.

Updating my forecast:

Update: Us Sens. Ted Cruz and Jeanne Shaheen are currently drafting a bill that will allow for US sanctions to be applied in relation to the work on the NordStream II project. Sanctions would affect the vessels involved in the construction, deny visas to those executives of the vessel companies, and companies that provide insurance for the parts of the project. The relationship with US is the center of Denmark's hesitancy to approve the project, as the US has long been Denmark's closest international ally. In proposing, and potentially approving such a bill, US lawmakers are underlining their opposition to the project and the political importance of it. Consequently, DK would have a hard time approving a project that an ally is sanctioning. This development only supports the hypothesis that Denmark will delay their decision even further. I adjust my predictions accordingly.

The Danish general election will take place at the 5th of June. It is very unlikely that the current prime minister and its government will decide about the Nord Stream 2 (NS2) project after they have been delaying it for the last years. It is more likely that the current government will postpone any decision to avoid responsibility in the case of a change of government. Additionally, the Danish Parliament will have its summer recess soon after the general election. As a result, it seems extremely unlikely that any decision will be made before the 31 of August 2019.

NORDSTREAM-Russia's Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project to Germany may launch in 2020, rather than the end of 2019, due to delays in obtaining permits from Denmark, Interfax news agency on Friday quoted Nord Stream 2 AG as saying.

Seeing as the pipeline plans was delayed in March 2019 (https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/denmark-delays-nord-stream-2-approval/), I find it highly unlikely that a decision will come before September 2019. With that being said, the people behind the Russian company that is currently constructing the pipeline have critiqued Danish politicians for not taking a decision, as the pipeline is fast approaching Bornholm, which could speed up the process. On the other hand, one must believe that the coming election will influence the choice, both the EU election and the Danish parliamentary elections. Some Danish politicians have expressed worries that the pipeline will undermine the EU's energy strategy, as well as the fact that Russia will use the pipeline to put pressure on other European states, and state that Russia has shown willingness to do this before. (https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/regionale/bornholm/omdiskuteret-gasledning-naermer-sig-danmark-dag-dag-politikerne-bruger).

The Danish position towards building the Nord Stream 2 route, that is often described as a "highly controversial project", has been quite obvious to be negative, since the country’s been trying hard to postpone making a final decision. It is believed by number of east European, Nordic and Baltic Sea countries that the Nord Stream 2 will increase EU dependence/resilience on Moscow. The major concerns that occurred over the past few years are: (1) the route will double the amount of Russian gas delivered to Germany through the Baltic States; (2) will “make little commercial sense”; and (3) will lead to “exert energy leverage over Western Europe” for Putin. In the beginning the European Commission, the Baltic States and Poland as well joined the United States in opposing to the idea of the pipeline. However, Finland, Sweden and Germany have already approved the construction of the pipeline. Therefore, the Danish refusal is a major challenge for the Gazprom project. Besides, in February 2019, the EU allowed the project to be proceeded, a deal that was compromising the positions of different states was introduced by Germany and France. The pipeline must meet several EU requirements and the process is going to be led by Germany.

"Danish newspaper Politiken referred to sources in the DEA to indicate that Denmark is highly likely to ask Nord Stream 2 to submit a third application including territorial waters between Poland and Bornholm. That may mean further delay the project and increase costs, as it may take up to one year to consider it." https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/denmark-delays-nord-stream-2-approval/

Update Danish elections have been announced on 5 June. As I stated in my previous forecast, the new government will take time to get established this summer, so I think that the topic will be again in the political debate after August. Then, Denmark will keep in trying to delay as much as possible the construction. Denmark doesn't want to antagonize superpowers as the US, so much against the NS2, plus, has submitted an application for a third route option for the pipeline: this act it's a strategy to postpone further the construction of the NS2. In spiete its will Denmark has not many tools to use. Indeed, "Denmark still has the possibility to veto the initial route option after it passed a law in 2017 that could allow it to ban the pipeline from passing through its territorial waters on security grounds. However, the veto cannot be applied for the two remaining applications as they would route the pipeline through Denmark’s exclusive economic zone waters but not its territorial waters." Moreover, in spite the issue is very tangled also for the EU, the pressures from Germany and the private companies in building the NS2 are quite high, plus the project is still supposed to be finished before the end of 2019. These new information (that I didn't had for my previous forecast) make me re-asset my prediction.

No need to say, NordStream 2 is a highly controversial project that goes way beyond just being an economic project. As it is argued by countries like Poland, the Baltic states and Ukraine, this is clearly the project that increases Russia's influence over Europe via dependence Russian gas. As harsh as it sounds, successfully implemented NordStream 2 would become a highly powerful tool in Putin's hands to do the impact on European decisions. In addition, this project goes against Europe's energy policy in terms of diversification of the energy sources and of transit countries within the EU itself (with the Nord Stream II pipeline, Russia would export even more towards the EU and Germany would acquire a predominant position as a point of entry of natural gas (30% of gas would be arriving in the EU via Germany, an increase from the current figure of 15%). Presenting the context, it quite well reveals the reasoning why Denmark is working so hard on delaying the approval. There are key points why I don't expect for Denmark to approve NordStream 2 before at least before December 2019:

Update: Denmark has submitted an application for a third route option for the pipeline. It appears the Danish authorities are trying to delay it's construction further -- showing allegiance with the U.S. The attempt to postpone is indicative of its general reluctance to approve the pipeline. Given that we are less than a month out from June 1, that Denmark will overcome this reluctance and suddenly approve construction is not foreseeable. Option1 is forecasted at 0%. As discussed in my original forecast on this question, ultimately Denmark will not have any decision-making power on a pipeline that does not go through it's territorial waters but will attempt to delay as long as possible. Since the pipeline is due to be complete at the end of the year, Denmark's approval will likely come as late as they possibly can make it -- after September. Nord Stream 2 has already said that it is on track, though Danish actions may push the completion date back. How long of a delay Denmark can create will determine when it's approval finally comes through. Equal weighting is given to each timeframe after September, accounting for their wish to postpone further on the one hand (giving an after December 1 approval) and their lack of veto power to really do anything about it on the other (giving a between September 1 and November 30 approval).
Forecast Update #4:

The current prognosis is based on a few considerations which put more weight in the possibility of a decision to be made in the end of the year and in my view, not before 1st December 2019 due to the details and current behavior of Danish authorities specifically surrounding the Danish permitting procedure.

Update: Manfred Weber, the conservative candidate to lead the EU commission, says that he will work to halt the Nord Stream II project, should he be chosen for the powerful position. This, I believe, only adds the Danish government's hesitancy to approve the Danish Nordstream route. In all likeliness, we will not see any decisions until after the new EU commissioners have been decided upon. (https://www.avisen.dk/tysk-eu-spidskandidat-vil-stoppe-nord-stream-2_548924.aspx)
Forecast Update #3:

First of all, Nord Stream 2 has become a highly controversial topic in Denmark and the EU and Danish elections will be happening within a few months. This would make any decision between Now and the end of June highly political and highly unlikely due to the fact that it would open up the current Danish Government to criticism. Therefore, it does make political sense for Denmark to approve the pipeline before June 2019. For this reason I think there is a 0% chance of that happening. Moreover, after the election, any new government would have to form a new cabinet and take time to transition to leadership and making a decision on Nord Stream 2 so early on has the potential to undermine the authority of the Danish government in the eyes of their voters. Therefore, I find it highly unlikely that it'll be approved soon after elections. Of course this logic really depends on the party platforms of running parties and which party wins the election, but since elections haven't started it is hard to speculate these factors.

While it seems very likely that Denmark will eventually approve the construction of Nord Stream 2, it appears unlikely that this will happen for the next few months. Denmark is the only country in the Nord Stream 2 projected pathway that has not yet approved the construction. Many of their neighbors such as Finland, Sweden and Germany have already signed off on the pipeline, so it seems only a matter of time before Denmark follows suit (1). However, Denmark already delayed the approval in late March, so the likelihood of the approval happening soon is low. The Danish Energy Agency reports that they delayed the approval to "investigate the environmental impacts for a route south of Bornholm in the continental shelf area." (1). Reports also suggest that the time it will take for Denmark to approve the pipeline could add years to the construction time, making it even more unlikely that the construction of the Nord Stream 2 be approved before December 2019 (2).

Denmark's block seems to be still in place (https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/denmark-delays-nord-stream-2-approval/ and https://www.politico.eu/article/nord-stream-2-runs-aground-in-denmark/). The most Nord Stream 2-optimist views talk about an approval from November on (https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gazprom-nordstream-2-denmark/nord-stream-2-upbeat-denmark-will-approve-gas-pipeline-proposal-idUSKCN1R61EM article wrote at the end of March, which says "Nord Stream 2 spokesman Jens Mueller said there was “good reason” to believe Danish authorities would process a second proposal submitted by the project in August 2018 within eight to 12 months, allowing the pipeline to be finished on schedule.").

Denmark’s hesitancy to approve the Nord Stream 2 is not so much a matter of energy, as it as a question of Denmark’s relations to Germany, Russia, and the US. Germany is Denmark’s most important European relation, whereas the US has long been the most prominent international ally. Lastly, Russia is of major importance in relation to Denmark’s pending negotiations in the Arctic. Hence, many interests need to be balanced.

Fossil fuel companies are going to have a much harder time pushing through legislation that promotes the use of their products. For this reason expansion of existing pipelines and the creation of new ones will be met with increasing resistance as more people push for alternatives.
delay by asking for info on southern route option should push this into next year.

Nord Stream 2 is a doubled of the already functioning Nord Stream and both start from Russia and end in Germany. - Denmark won't approve in the immediate future the construction of Nord Stream 2 because of the upcoming national elections (it’s impossible to approve it before June), plus, the parties are now focused on the electoral campaign. - the main reason why Denmark won't approve the agreement even in the next future because it is against the dependency on Russian gas - Denmark has also some disputes ongoing with Russia and other countries about claiming Arctic territories, a situation that wouldn’t facilitate the progress of this project - currently, no one of the main parties (Liberal and Social Democrats) is in favour of Nord stream 2, and I don't think it would be the core proposal of the political programme from election winner. For this reason, I'm skeptical also about the idea of approving it in the months following the election, which will be a government transition period. - in the end of 2018 Denmark has put an end to the dispute with Poland about the maritime borders in the Baltic Sea: this has allowed Danish Emergency Agency to ask for an evaluation of the eventual environmental risks caused by the pipeline. We should remember Denmark is very concerned about environmental issues - EU is also skeptical for multiple reasons: it doesn’t want to rely on Russia dependency on gas, in particular now that the sanctions are still active and because of the unresolved dispute in Crimea. Moreover, EU has recently changed the project, and now it’s under the European Law. Also, for EU this stream represents an energy security issue, because Gazprom has the monopole of the pipeline. - EU is already building the TAP (trans Adriatic pipeline), in order to diversify gas supplies importing it from Azerbaijan. I don’t see a lot of coherence in implementing a project as Nord Stream 2, with the opposite effect of relying on Russian supplies. - Russia has launched an alternative to bypass Denmark, focusing on the Balcan route and export gas through those countries - Among the "against Nord stream 2" there are US, Baltic countries and Poland, all of them worried about the rely of Europe on Russian gas. US is an historical competitor of Russia in the economic military and political fields, while Poland and Baltic states have historically been scared and threatened by the power of Russia, so their rejection is due to this fear

Based on Denmark's recent environmental review request, I think it is likely there will be substancial delays to the project and the country will simply keep adding delays until the project is either redesigned or canceled.

New information shows that Denmark is adding more environmental review requests that could take over a year to complete. As we all know the relations between Russia and the EU have been stiffening over the recent years, especially after the Russian unilateral annexation of Crimea and the following European economic sanctions. However, even though Russia is under sanctions, Nord Stream 2 (from now on NS2), a Russia-Germany undersea gas pipe that has divided Europeans and angered America, is not. Day by day, the companies contracted by Gazprom, the Russian state-owned gas giant and NS2’s sole shareholder, are laying their concrete-coated steel pipe segments on the bed of the Baltic Sea. They aim to finish by the end of the year (https://www.economist.com/europe/2019/02/16/the-nord-stream-2-gas-pipeline-moves-on).

Denmark has been skeptical of the nord stream 2 project because of many reasons, but primarily because it does not want to rely on Russian Gas. This is a position that is not likely to change over time, as is shown by a bill by the EU passed yesterday that denounces Russia as a s'trategic partner' (https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/russia-cant-be-considered-strategic-partner-of-eu-anymore-meps-say/)

Denmark's government is postponing its final decision on the approval of the construction of Nord Stream 2, also due to the upcoming elections (which make it almost impossible for the approval to be made before June). The pipeline will make it possible for more gas to be transported from Russia to Germany, which is thus trying to exercise pressure on Denmark to allow the construction. On the other side, the USA are opposing the project and do not want the traditional routes via Ukraine to be bypassed. Austrian energy group OMV , one of the companies that is financing the Nord Stream 2 pipeline, is optimistic Denmark will approve the project this year and the new gas transport route will start operations late 2019 (https://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFL8N1XB68G). Similarly, according to the European Commissioner for Budget and Human Resources Günther Hermann Oettinger, "the pipeline has been under construction for a long time and may not be halted so easily anymore" (https://polandin.com/40640045/nord-stream-2-cannot-be-stopped-now-eu-commissioner). In my opinion therefore, it is likely that the final approval will arrive in the second half of the year, once a new government will be formed, and with no further delay.

Denmark is the last state yet to approve the construction of Nord Stream 2, which is set to run through its exclusive economic zone (not territorial waters). Thus far it has been delaying the approval, and has implemented laws allowing it to refuse the the pipeline on a security basis — this can be seen as a strategic move, as the pipeline has faced opposition from the US (an important economic partner to Denmark). With or without Danish permits though, the project was never going to be derailed since its EEZ is effectively governed by international laws.

Since 14 Months Russia has been waiting for an answer from Copenhagen with regard to its gas transmission pipeline Nord Stream 2. The Danish government is the last one, whose approval is still pending. That the project has not proved very popular with the Danish government becomes clear by looking at the approval process to date. Only after Nord Stream 2 submitted its application, the Danish parliament passed the amendment of the Continental Shelf Act (01/01/2018), which enables the Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs to veto infrastructure projects handled by the Danish Energy Agency (DEA) in case they run contrary to Danish security interests (https://www.ndr.de/nachrichten/mecklenburg-vorpommern/Nord-Stream-2-Daenemark-lehnt-geplante-Route-ab,nordstream302.html). Predicting a possible negative outcome, Nord Stream 2 AG proposed an alternative route - 36 km longer than the original one - but outside of Danish territorial waters, only running through its exclusive economic zone (EEZ). This route can only be prevented/delayed by serious safety or logistical concerns - not political ones. It is considered highly unlikely Denmark would risk rejecting a project in its EEZ for obvious political reasons, given that it has historically relied so heavily on commerce from its important trading route waters. The government would risk being seen as an untrustworthy maritime operator (https://www.forbes.com/sites/davekeating/2018/09/05/as-of-today-russias-controversial-nord-stream-2-pipeline-is-already-underwater/).

Denmark is postponing the approval for the construction of Nord Stream 2 for political reasons which opposes the context where Nord Stream 1 was built. If Rasmussen was expecting the UE to back up on the motives not to approve Nord Stream 2, Denmark can no longer refuse the route to go through Danish waters as the Union has just declared that it won’t block the project (https://politiken.dk/udland/art7031352/Nord-Stream-2-gasledningen-får-grønt-lys-fra-EU). The construction of the pipeline is in process and I expect the works to arrive near Denmark in the following months (mid-summer). In that sense, I expect Denmark not to make a decision before the works come to proximity but in late July-August. In additon, I believe that for economic interests; because the UE is not much willing to hinder the project; and because the German-Russian project will go through Danish waters anyways (using the alternative of EEZ), it is most likely that Denmark will approve the construction of Nord Stream 2 through its territorial waters. If it is still possible that the works arrive in Denmark’s waters at the end of the Summer because of further potential delay, it is most likely that the decision will be made during September/early October, not later.

The very focal point in here is that Denmark is very unlikely to endorse the pipeline's contruction any soon (https://russiabusinesstoday.com/energy/denmark-still-deciding-on-nord-stream-2-approval/), or that Denmark will actually ever want to build it. If Russian, German and Gazprom's lobbying will be succesful, it will require time, and a careful bargaining over Denamrk's interests. I think the most likely outcome will be an impatient Gazprom tired of waiting and eventually deciding to adopt the more costly, but possibly time efficient plan B avoiding Denmark's exclusive economic zone - the fact that there is a plan B could be a bargaining device to speed up Denamrk's decision-making or an actual sign that the project will be done without Copenhagen's approval.

Denmark is the last country involved in the Nord Stream 2 project to have not agreed to the construction of the pipeline. Concerned by geopolitical reasons, especially with Russia, Denmark rejects the project, seeing a political negative impact rather than an economic benefit, as see Germany. Gazprom, the Russian company that is driving the project, has already applied for the first pipeline route in April 2017. Nevertheless, Denmark has made a wait-and-see attitude, asking for a greater examination of the environmental impacts, through an Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA). Nord Stream 2 to counter this voluntary delay submitted on August 10, 2018 a second building permit, allocated with an EIA, for an alternative route in the northwest of Bornholm, this time. This second request is different than the first one, as the second route passes through Denmark's Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ), where its jurisdiction is severely diminished, unlike the first route through the Danish territorial waters. This second route is only 36km longer than the first, which is not a major obstacle, and Denmark would not be able to block it anymore. In addition, work on the pipeline has already begun, and the closer they get to Denmark, the sooner the construction agreement, whether in its territorial waters or in the EEZ, will be felt. Denmark is going to decided very soon between the two projects, due to the arrival of the pipeline near its waters, and can not therefore refuse an agreement, because the second alternative will be done automatically if the first route is not accepted, and Denmark will therefore lose economic profits due to a excessive wait-and-see attitude. In addition, it should be noted that the Nord Stream 1 project was approved in the Danish waters and is still in service, which strengthens the chances of an agreement in 2019, because the geopolitical consequences in the case of a bad scenario will be there anyway. Secondly, the EIA for the alternative route has shown that the pipeline would have a minor, negligible, and not significant effect for the environment, but also for tourism and even military practices. There is no impact at all. (Source: https: //ens.dk/sites/ens.dk/files/OlieGas/11_-_environmental_impact_assessment_denmark._nord_stream_2_-_north-western_route._august_2018.pdf). I believe that the construction of the pipeline will reach Danish waters between July and September 2019, and that a response will be made right after this arrival or by the end of 2019 at the latest.

The Danish government delayed the approval because it was not just about gas and energy policy but about positioning Denmark in the international and diplomatic context (choosing between Russia, Germany on one side and the US on other) [1]. The Danish government hoped that the European Union would block the project thereby avoiding having to make the decision themselves [2]. The EU decided to not block the project, though with some conditions. This has put pressure back on the Danish foreign minister to deliver his considerations on the foreign policy and security dimension of the project, since his approval is one of the last remaining steps. Wanting to avoid further controversies with Germany and Russia, there is a 55% probability that an approval will arrive before June 1st.
